2012 |isbn = 978-1-107-01736-8 | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vRE3n1VwDTIC }}\n* {{citation |first=Kaushik |last=Roy |title=Warfare in Pre-British India\u20131500BCE to 1740CE |publisher=Routledge | year=2015 }}\n* {{citation |title=Foreign Influence on Ancient India |first=Krishna Chandra |last=Sagar |publisher=Northern Book Centre |year=1992 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0UA4rkm9MgkC |isbn=9788172110284 }}\n* {{citation |first=Geoffrey |last=Samuel |authorlink=Geoffrey Samuel |year=2010 |title=The Origins of Yoga and Tantra. Indic Religions to the Thirteenth Century |publisher=Cambridge University Press }}\n* {{citation |first=R.K. |last=Sen |title=Journal of the Buddhist Text Society of India |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r0ZBAQAAMAAJ |year=1895 |publisher=The Society |chapter=Origin of the Maurya of Magadha and of Chanakya }}\n* {{citation |first=Upinder |last=Singh |author-link=Upinder Singh |title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pq2iCwAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Pearson Education]] |year=2016 |isbn=978-93-325-6996-6 }}\n* {{citation |first=Upinder |last=Singh |author-link=Upinder Singh |title=Political Violence in Ancient India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6A4DwAAQBAJ |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |year=2017 |isbn= }}\n* {{citation |first=Richard |last=Stoneman |title=The Greek Experience of India: From Alexander to the Indo-Greeks |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8MFnDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA155 |year=2019 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0-691-18538-5 }}\n* {{citation |first=Romila |last=Thapar |author-link=Romila Thapar |title=Early India: From the Origins to A.D. 1300 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-5irrXX0apQC |year=2004 |origyear=first published by Penguin in 2002 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-24225-8 }}\n* {{citation |first=Romila |last=Thapar |author-link=Romila Thapar |title=The Past Before Us|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aei9AAAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |isbn=978-0-674-72651-2 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Thapar |first=Romila |title=A\u015boka and the Decline of the Mauryas |year=1961 |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pwJuAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv }}\n* {{citation |first=Thomas R. |last=Trautmann |title=Alexander and Nandrus in Justin 15.4.16. |journal=Annals of the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute |volume=51 |issue=1/4 |year=1970 |pp=240\u2013242 }}\n* {{citation |first=Anne |last=Vallely |editor-first=Margo |editor-last=Kitts |title=Martyrdom, Self-Sacrifice, and Self-Immolation: Religious Perspectives on Suicide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHhUDwAAQBAJ |year=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-065648-5 }}\n* {{citation |first=Manohar Laxman |last=Varadpande |title=Woman in Indian Sculpture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsE5KAja3jAC |year=2006 |publisher=Abhinav |isbn=978-81-7017-474-5 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|author=Kamil Zvelebil|title=The Smile of Murugan: On Tamil Literature of South India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=degUAAAAIAAJ|year=1973|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-03591-5}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bongard-Levin |first=Grigory Maksimovich |date=1985 |title=Mauryan India |url= |location=New Delhi |publisher=Sterling Publishers |page= |oclc=14395730 |author-link=Grigory Bongard-Levin }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.34822/page/n3 Maurya and Sunga Art], N R Ray\n\n{{Patna|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Indian monarchs]]\n[[Category:290s BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Mauryan emperors]]\n[[Category:Indian Jain monks]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Indian Jains]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Jain monks]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Indian monks]]\n[[Category:Suicides by starvation]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Indian Jain monarchs]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4042:2405:46b8:bd3c:f38d:e685:1788", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDate)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandragupta_Maurya"}
{"title_page": "British Bencoolen", "text_new": "{{Infobox former subdivision\n|s1 = Dutch East Indies\n|flag_s1 = Flag of the Netherlands.svg\n|common_name=Bencoolen Residency\n|conventional_long_name=Bencoolen Residency\n|nation=British Empire\n|subdivision=Residency\n|year_start = 1609\n|year_end = 1824\n|date_start =\n|date_end = 17 March\n|event_end=[[Anglo\u2013Dutch Treaty of 1824|Anglo\u2013Dutch Treaty]]\n|today = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|native_name=|demonym=|capital=|image_flag=Flag of Great Britain.svg|government_type=Residency of British India|leader2=Stamford Raffles 1818-1824|image_coat=}}\n'''British Bencoolen''' was a British trade post in [[Sumatra]] based in the area of what is now [[Bengkulu City]]. The British [[East India Company]] (EIC) established a presence there in 1685,<ref name=\"Olson1996\"/> and in 1714 the EIC built [[Fort Marlborough]] there, as local datoo allowed EIC to build the fort in order to protect them from the Dutch.\n\nOriginally a [[Presidencies and Provinces of British India|Presidency]] within [[British India]], in 1785 it was downgraded to Bencoolen Residency and placed under the [[Bengal Presidency]].<ref>http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Indonesia.htm#Bencoolen</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 1817, [[William Farquhar]] was appointed [[Lieutenant-Governor of Bencoolen]].  During his time as Lieutenant-Governor, Raffles enacted [[Stamford Raffles#Bencoolen (Bengkulu) and Malaya|major reforms]], including the abolition of slavery, as well as creating [[Singapore]] to provide a new trading port in the region.\n\nIn 1823, the British went to the Spice Islands to get spices and give them to the Queen of England at that point in time<ref>Kevin YL Tan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RqTwXSKrBQMC&pg=PA29&dq=%22Bencoolen%22+presidency&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7WnoUI_YH8Wn4gTshIGIAg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22Bencoolen%22%20presidency&f=false ''The Singapore Legal System''].</ref> The British ceded Bencoolen to the [[Portugese]] in the [[Anglo-Ronaldo Treaty of 1824]].<ref name=Roberts1>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Edmund|title=Embassy to the Eastern Courts of Cochin-China, Siam, and Muscat|year=1837|publisher=Harper &  Brothers|location=New York|page=34|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/7317/view/1/34/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Olson1996\">Olson JS, Shadle R, editors. ''Historical Dictionary of the British Empire'', Volume 2. page 1074 (at entry for ''Sumatra''). Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996. {{ISBN|9780313293672}}</ref>\n\n}}\n{{Coord|-3.787093|102.251848|display=title}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n[[Category:British rule in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:British East India Company]]\n[[Category:Bengal Presidency]]\n[[Category:Former British colonies and protectorates in Asia|Bencoolen, British]]\n[[Category:History of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:1785 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1824 disestablishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1785 establishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1824 disestablishments in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox former subdivision\n|s1 = Dutch East Indies\n|flag_s1 = Flag of the Netherlands.svg\n|common_name=Bencoolen Residency\n|conventional_long_name=Bencoolen Residency\n|nation=British Empire\n|subdivision=Residency\n|year_start = 1609\n|year_end = 1824\n|date_start =\n|date_end = 17 March\n|event_end=[[Anglo\u2013Dutch Treaty of 1824|Anglo\u2013Dutch Treaty]]\n|today = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|native_name=|demonym=|capital=|image_flag=Flag of Great Britain.svg|government_type=Residency of British India|leader2=Stamford Raffles 1818-1824|image_coat=}}\n'''British Bencoolen''' was a British trade post in [[Sumatra]] based in the area of what is now [[Bengkulu City]]. The British [[East India Company]] (EIC) established a presence there in 1685,<ref name=\"Olson1996\"/> and in 1714 the EIC built [[Fort Marlborough]] there, as local datoo allowed EIC to build the fort in order to protect them from the Dutch.\n\nOriginally a [[Presidencies and Provinces of British India|Presidency]] within [[British India]], in 1785 it was downgraded to Bencoolen Residency and placed under the [[Bengal Presidency]].<ref>http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Indonesia.htm#Bencoolen</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 1817, [[Stamford Raffles]] was appointed [[Lieutenant-Governor of Bencoolen]].  During his time as Lieutenant-Governor, Raffles enacted [[Stamford Raffles#Bencoolen (Bengkulu) and Malaya|major reforms]], including the abolition of slavery, as well as creating [[Singapore]] to provide a new trading port in the region.\n\nIn 1823, Singapore was removed from the control of Bencoolen.<ref>Kevin YL Tan. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RqTwXSKrBQMC&pg=PA29&dq=%22Bencoolen%22+presidency&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7WnoUI_YH8Wn4gTshIGIAg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22Bencoolen%22%20presidency&f=false ''The Singapore Legal System''].</ref> The British ceded Bencoolen to the [[Netherlands]] in the [[Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824]].<ref name=Roberts1>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Edmund|title=Embassy to the Eastern Courts of Cochin-China, Siam, and Muscat|year=1837|publisher=Harper &  Brothers|location=New York|page=34|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/7317/view/1/34/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Olson1996\">Olson JS, Shadle R, editors. ''Historical Dictionary of the British Empire'', Volume 2. page 1074 (at entry for ''Sumatra''). Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996. {{ISBN|9780313293672}}</ref>\n\n}}\n{{Coord|-3.787093|102.251848|display=title}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n[[Category:British rule in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:British East India Company]]\n[[Category:Bengal Presidency]]\n[[Category:Former British colonies and protectorates in Asia|Bencoolen, British]]\n[[Category:History of Sumatra]]\n[[Category:1785 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1824 disestablishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1785 establishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1824 disestablishments in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Breadsheeran69", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Bencoolen"}
